<br />
Whew. Well there you have it. Below is a more advanced strat. You might want to try playing the deck first, but I’m sure it wouldn’t hurt to look at. Happy Gaming, and welcome to LOTR.<br />
<br />
<br />
ADVANCED STRATEGY:<br />
<br />
If you’ve stuck with me this long (or even just scrolled down to here). Here then is the basic strat.<br />
<br />
Bid 1-3 which means you’ll have two to four burdens including smeagol. Sam and Faramir will be able to remove some of those, so your all set. If you win, choose to go first, from where you can grab gorn. If not, it means your opponent will hit the cavern entrenace and deep of helm. I’d bid 3 normally, but I’m not sure.<br />
<br />
I would reccomend NOT doubling to 3, unless your opponent went first and did. The reason is that it will give you more time to suit up the fellowship and stack your hand with shadow. After that you can run with reckelles abandon, or try to swarm. Or do both &#61514;<br />
<br />
Why no boromir? I simply judged that Smeagol, Sam, and Eown in particular were all more genreally useful. Why 2 aragorn and 3 faramir? I figured that faramir was actually better, plus it is important to get him so the bow can be played (can’t be played on aragorn). As well, there is a chance to get gorn anyways.<br />
<br />
Tidings of erebor is power. I used to have delving and search far and wide to cycle the deck better, but I din’t like the exertion of delving or the discard of search far and wide (it isn’t actaully moria). I then stumbled upon this. Most of the time they won’t have 3, so you get your cards, which can help you either double or set up the shadow hand a lttile. If they do, minus 3 twilight means an easier double move. I’d reccomend playing it even if you want to stop and they have 3, as you can’t afford to clog your hand.<br />
<br />
Shoulder to shoulder will probably primarilly be used to heal Gimli. In conjuction with Legolas’s sword it’s really good. You can also use it to fill up the pool for deep in thought, but just remeber Tidings won’t work effectively that turn.<br />
<br />
The shadow is rather simple. Draw mass amounts of cards with Abandoning and “Hate and Anger” (spot uruk and a moria orc to draw 3), and use ambition to reduce the costs. I considered Saruman’s power to deal with trust, but judging by Gullecram’s report, Rohan and RBR were the most popular, and I also didn’t want to get rid of my ambitions.<br />
<br />
Hope you liked it!<br />
